definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a beta-D-xylosyl residue from UDP-D-xylose to the serine hydroxyl group of an acceptor protein substrate.
Functions to provide a physical support for the assembly of a multiprotein receptor signaling complex.
Functions as a physical support bridging the N-methyl-D-aspartate receptor-PSD-95-GKAP complex and the mGluR-Homer complex, which are involved in receptor signaling in synapses.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a PDZ domain of a protein, a domain found in diverse signaling proteins.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a low-density lipoprotein particle, a lipoprotein particle that is rich in cholesterol esters and low in triglycerides, is typically composed of APOB100 and APOE, and has a density of 1.02-1.06 g|ml and a diameter of between 20-25 nm.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with pyridoxal 5' phosphate, 3-hydroxy-5-(hydroxymethyl)-2-methyl4-pyridine carboxaldehyde 5' phosphate, the biologically active form of vitamin B6.

Catalysis of the transmembrane transfer of a proton by a voltage-gated channel. A voltage-gated channel is a channel whose open state is dependent on the voltage across the membrane in which it is embedded.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with troponin C, the calcium-binding subunit of the troponin complex.

The component of the Golgi membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that have some part that penetrates at least one leaflet of the membrane bilayer. This component includes gene products that are buried in the bilayer with no exposure outside the bilayer.
Thin, stiff protrusion extended by the leading edge of a motile cell such as a crawling fibroblast or amoeba, or an axonal or dendritic growth cone, or a dendritic shaft.

label.value: integral component of endoplasmic reticulum membrane

definition.value: The component of the endoplasmic reticulum membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that have some part that penetrates at least one leaflet of the membrane bilayer. This component includes gene products that are buried in the bilayer with no exposure outside the bilayer.
Enables the directed movement of nitric oxide, nitrogen monoxide, from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the reaction -  formamide -eq- H(2)O + hydrogen cyanide.
Functions as a lubricant for an extracellular matrix, such as a mucous membrane.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with semaphorin receptors.
Combining with an apolipoprotein to initiate a change in cell activity.

Combining with a lipoprotein particle and delivering the lipoprotein particle into the cell via endocytosis. A lipoprotein particle, also known as a lipoprotein, is a clathrate complex consisting of a lipid enwrapped in a protein host without covalent binding in such a way that the complex has a hydrophilic outer surface consisting of all the protein and the polar ends of any phospholipids.
Combining with a very-low-density lipoprotein particle and delivering the very-low-density lipoprotein into the cell via endocytosis.
Transcription factor complex that binds to the insulin control element (ICE), a DNA sequence element found within the 5'-flanking region of the insulin gene, and activates ICE-mediated transcription.
Catalyzes transport of all four deoxy (d) NDPs, and, less efficiently, the corresponding dNTPs, in exchange for dNDPs, ADP, or ATP.
Binds to and modulates the activity of an enzyme.
Modulates the activity of nitric oxide synthase.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any carbohydrate, which includes monosaccharides, oligosaccharides and polysaccharides as well as substances derived from monosaccharides by reduction of the carbonyl group (alditols), by oxidation of one or more hydroxy groups to afford the corresponding aldehydes, ketones, or carboxylic acids, or by replacement of one or more hydroxy group(s) by a hydrogen atom. Cyclitols are generally not regarded as carbohydrates.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any polysaccharide, a polymer of many (typically more than 10) monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with cellulose.
Modulates the activity of guanylate cyclase.
Increases the activity of guanylate cyclase.
Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of guanylate cyclase.

label.value: type I protein secretion system complex

definition.value: A complex of three secretory proteins that carry out secretion in the type I secretion system -  an inner membrane transport ATPase (termed ABC protein for ATP-binding cassette), which provides the energy for protein secretion -  an outer membrane protein, which is exported via the sec pathway -  and a membrane fusion protein, which is anchored in the inner membrane and spans the periplasmic space.

label.value: type III protein secretion system complex

definition.value: A complex of approximately 20 proteins, most of which are located in the cytoplasmic membrane that carries out protein secretion in the bacterial type III secretion system -  type III secretion also requires a cytoplasmic, probably membrane-associated ATPase.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (-)-quinate + NAD+ -eq- (-)-3-dehydroquinate + NADH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  glycolate + NADP+ -eq- glyoxylate + NADPH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5,10-methylenetetrahydromethanopterin + coenzyme F420 + 2 H(+) -eq- 5,10-methenyl-5,6,7,8-tetrahydromethanopterin + reduced coenzyme F420.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5-methyltetrahydromethanopterin + coenzyme M -eq- 5,6,7,8-tetrahydromethanopterin + methyl-coenzyme M. 2-(methylthio)ethanesulfonate is also known as methyl-CoM.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5,6,7,8-tetrahydromethanopterin + N-formylmethanofuran + H(+) -eq- N(5)-formyl-5,6,7,8-tetrahydromethanopterin + methanofuran.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5-formyltetrahydrofolate + ATP -eq- 5,10-methenyltetrahydrofolate + ADP + H(+) + phosphate.
Combining with the cyclic peptide hormone melanin-concentrating hormone to initiate a change in cell activity.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a LIM domain (for Lin-11 Isl-1 Mec-3) of a protein, a domain with seven conserved cysteine residues and a histidine, that binds two zinc ions and acts as an interface for protein-protein interactions.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a LRR domain (leucine rich repeats) of a protein.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a clathrin heavy or light chain, the main components of the coat of coated vesicles and coated pits, and which also occurs in synaptic vesicles.
The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of an epidermal cutaneous structure.
The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of cutaneous epidermal structures such as hairs, scales, or feathers.
Catalysis of the reaction -  testosterone + NAD(P)+ -eq- androst-4-ene-3,17-dione + NAD(P)H + H+.
Combining with estrogen and transmitting the signal within the cell to trigger a change in cell activity or function.

label.value: integral component of synaptic vesicle membrane

definition.value: The component of the synaptic vesicle membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that have some part that penetrates at least one leaflet of the membrane bilayer. This component includes gene products that are buried in the bilayer with no exposure outside the bilayer.
Any of several large complexes that contain two or three dynein heavy chains and several light chains, and have microtubule motor activity.
The region between the plasma membrane and the cell wall, as found in organisms such as yeast and Gram positive bacteria. The region is thinner than the equivalent in Gram negative bacteria.

The region between the inner (cytoplasmic or plasma) membrane and outer membrane of organisms with two membranes such as Gram negative bacteria. These periplasmic spaces are relatively thick and contain a thin cell wall.
The complex formed by the catalytic subunit of protein phosphatase 4 plus a regulatory subunit.

Any of a group of peptide cofactors of enzymes for the lysosomal degradation of sphingolipids. They stimulate various enzymes, including glucosylceramidase, galactosylceramidase, cerebroside-sulfatase, alpha-galactosidase, beta-galactosidase, and sphingomyelin phosphodiesterase.
